b'' b'' b'--' b'' b'i would like to be able to detect the angular position (low accuracy) of an' b'ir emitting source at a distance of about meters (more is better) in' b"daylight. the ir source could be emitting a signature; i'm leaning toward" b'30 khz square wave with duty cycle.' b'' b'i am considering the use of a quadrant detector from centronic inc. to give' b'information to a pan/tilt head to point the sensor and thus determine the' b'angles. for the source i am considering wazing the heck out of an ir led(s),' b'possibly an optek op290 or motorola mled81. wazing would mean at least amp' b'current pulses. at this current the duty cycle of the led drops to and i' b'would need to cycle five of them in turn to get the required.' b'' b'has anyone done something like this?' b'' b'(403) dre suffield, box medicine hat, ab, canada, t1a 8k6' b'' b'a method which will directly (almost) provide you with the information that' b'you require is that which is commonly used for coordinate measurements of' b'human body landmarks (eg. the selspot system by selspot ab, sweden, and the' b'watsmart system these use lateral photoeffect detectors [lindholm and' b'oberg, woltring and marsolais, to determine the position of a' b'spot of light projected (using a camera lens) over its surface. in escence,' b'the detector is a large photodiode with four cathodes (one on each of the' b'four sides of the square detector crystal) and a single anode (the back of' b'the crystal). a spot of light will produce currents which are proportional' b"to the position of the spot on the detector's face. let's try some ascii" b'graphics in 2-d (so the detector has two cathodes to detect linear position)' b'' b'' b'' b'------------------------- b'| b'| b'----- cathode b'xxxxx b'xxxxx| b'light xxxxx| divider output' b'xxxxx| b'xxxxx|-----| b'xxxxx| b'xxxxx| gnd b'xxxxx| b'xxxxx| anode b'xxxxx b'----- cathode b'| b'| b'-------------------------- b'' b'if the dot of light from the led is the only source of light, then the position' b'of the projection is given by this circuit regardless of the level of illumina-' b'tion (the divider is used to normalize relative to total received power). when' b'this circuit is used in the presence of other sources of light, then the way of' b'"tuning" to it is to sample for a few msec the background signal, light the led' b'for an equal time and sample that signal separately. the difference between' b'the two is the position of the led.' b'' b'hamamatsu photonics sells linear and 2-d lateral photoeffect detectors, and' b'they also sell the required signal processing electronics. the ready-made' b'systems by selspot and others are not cheap b'' b'lindholm, l.e., and k.e. oberg, "an optoelectronic instrument for remote' b'on-line movement monitoring", biotelemetry, b'' b'woltring, h.j., and e.b. marsolais, "opto-electronic (selspot) gait measure-' b'ments in two and three dimensional space a preliminary report", bull. pros-' b'thetics research, b'' b'most probably this technique can provide you with a much more accurate' b'measurement than you need, but i think that its simplicity beats scanning' b'a quadrant detector with a pan/tilt system until you reach zero difference.' b'' b'- david' b'' b'' b'' b'+------------------------------------------------------------+' b'| david prutchi hc1dt b'| one brookings drive b'| st. louis, mo b'+------------------------------------------------------------+' 